{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"350b7895-324b-4e8f-b60f-449c34864f31","content":"Yes, both are known MSTest v4 breaking changes. Here's what's happening:\n\n## 1. Lost test history in Azure DevOps\n\nMSTest v4 changed how **test IDs are computed** (the fully qualified test name format). Azure DevOps tracks tests by ID, so they all appear as new tests. You can restore the old ID scheme by adding this to your `.runat` or project file:\n\n```xml\n<MSTestV4IdCompat>true</MSTestV4IdCompat>\n```\n\nOr, accept the one-time history reset.\n\n## 2. `TestContext.TestName` in `[ClassInitialize]`\n\nIn v4, the `TestContext` passed to `[ClassInitialize]` is now a **class-level context** — it's no longer (incorrectly) tied to a specific test. Accessing `TestName` throws `InvalidOperationException` because no test is in scope yet.\n\n**Fix for your code** — remove the `TestName` access since it's meaningless at class-init time:\n\n```csharp\n[ClassInitialize]\npublic static void ClassInit(TestContext context)\n{\n    // context.TestName is not available here in v4\n    // Use context for class-level logging only\n}\n```\n\nIf you need per-test setup, use `[TestInitialize]` instead, where `TestContext.TestName` is valid.\n\n## 3. Other v4 gotchas to watch for\n\n| Area | Change |\n|---|---|\n| **Default runner** | v4 defaults to the **MSTest runner** instead of VSTest; CI scripts using `vstest.console.exe` may need updating |\n| **Parallelism** | Class-level parallelism is on by default; tests assuming sequential execution may break |\n| **`[DataRow(null)]`** | Passing `null` as the first arg now requires `new object[] { null }` to avoid ambiguity |\n| **Timeout behavior** | `[Timeout]` now uses `CancellationToken` cooperatively; infinite-hang tests won't be force-killed the same way |\n| **`Assert.AreEqual` on doubles** | Floating-point comparison tolerance handling was tightened |\n\nThe biggest silent risk is the **parallelism default** — if your tests share static state or database fixtures, you may see intermittent failures. Add `[assembly: Parallelize(Scope = ExecutionScope.MethodLevel)]` or `DoNotParallelize` explicitly to control this.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"122e4f60-edd1-43d5-8cd3-7e6fb6574359","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about MSTest v4 breaking changes. Let me provide what I know about MSTest v4 changes based on my knowledge, and also look at their specific code.\n\nKey MSTest v4 breaking changes:\n\n1. **Fully Qualified Test Names (FQN) changed** — MSTest v4 changed how test IDs are computed. The default test ID generation now uses a different scheme, which means Azure DevOps (and other CI systems that track tests by ID) see them as entirely new tests, losing history. This is the cause of their \"brand new tests with no history\" issue.\n\n2. **TestContext in ClassInitialize** — In MSTest v3, the `TestContext` passed to `[ClassInitialize]` had `TestName` populated (somewhat incorrectly, as class init isn't tied to a specific test). \n\nIn v4, that context is now properly scoped to the class level rather than a specific test method, so accessing `TestName` throws an `InvalidOperationException` since there's no test in scope during class initialization.\n\n3. **Other breaking changes** include `DataRow` no longer accepting `null` directly as the first argument (requiring the `new object[] { null }` pattern instead), changes to `DeploymentItem` behavior, and assembly-level `[Parallelize]` becoming the default in certain configurations.","outputTokens":1058,"requestId":"5C21:31910B:3F2860:4FEAB9:69F5649B"},"id":"0ec92162-2637-4a6d-a734-abc32d78d16d","timestamp":"2026-05-02T02:43:00.461Z","parentId":"a38ccfea-5eff-4040-9110-6df080749a57"}
